ce:section.ce:para:
Heteroatoms such as N and S in organic compounds can easily fill in the unoccupied 3d orbitals outside the Fe atoms owing to the lone pair electrons, and coordinate bonds are formed between heteroatoms and carbon steel surface. The content (wt.%) of N and S elements in N, S-CDs were up to 10.08% and 10.17%, respectively. As shown in FTIR (Fig. 2d), the synthetized N, S-CDs possess abundant functional groups, including hydroxyl, amino, and carbonyl groups. The existence of Fe-S in XPS (Fig. 4) illustrated that a part of the functional groups is distributed on the surface of N, S-CDs so that they can be tightly adsorbed on carbon steel. The polarization curve (Fig. 9) shows that N, S-CDs function as adsorbent inhibitor, prevent the dissolution of anode for carbon steel, and depress the cathodic evolution reaction. In addition, the effects of blocking the active sites and geometric blocking on the metal surface exist simultaneously. A theoretical model has been established to elucidate adsorption and inhibition (Fig. 13
                        ). The N, S-CD approached the surface of carbon steel through diffusion and formed coordinate covalent bonds by groups containing N and S with the active sites on the surface. Hence, a portion of N, S-CDs was fixed on the surface via chemisorption, and then the remaining N, S-CDs in the solution diffused to the metal surface in an agglomeration effect to reduce the specific surface area and maintain stability. The existence of functional groups on their surface may result in strong tendency for N, S-CDs to attract one another and produce enormous agglomerates (nanoparticles) when the remaining N, S-CDs are close to each other [55,57]. Furthermore, surface roughness and special micro-nanostructure, such as lotus leaf, considerably affect the wettability of the surface and is important for hydrophobicity [58,59]. Shen et al. [60] proposed that the nanoparticles are one of the determinants for the hydrophobic properties of the coating. Thus, the N, S-CDs nanoparticles adhered to the metal surface and formed the hydrophobic film that can prevent the corrosion medium and hydrone to form a direct contact with carbon steel. From contact angle (Fig. 7) and EIS (Figs. 10 and 11) measurements, the contact angle increased from 43° to 92° and the R
                        f substantially increased with the addition of N, S-CDs, thereby demonstrating considerable adsorption and hydrophobicity relative to the inhibitor. Therefore, the inhibition effect of N, S-CDs is associated with chemisorption from functional groups and hydrophobicity for nanoparticles.
